52

The entire day -- to 4 P.M.--in catching up with a number of unfinished items, mostly bibliographic in preparation for my eastern trip. Hate to quit actual writing of the Habits section of the paper, but it seems advisable to so in order that the eastern trip and library visits can be most efficient.

Am investigating old snake bite cases in the medical journals--mostly 1800-1860--to get the history of treatments; also such notes as the doctors included on the snakes themselves and how people happen to get bitten.

Then i have started a deeper investigation than was originally intended into ancient and medieval fold lore and treatment to learn the sources of as many stories and beliefs as possible.

Page Edit History:
  • lkairy 06/05/2014 12:57 PM
  • pamg 09/08/2012 07:33 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:54 PM

75

Worked at the N. Y. Public Library from 11 AM to 1 P.M--long enough to get somewhat acquainted with the methods and layout.

Signed bonds from 1:45 to 2:45. A gueer experience. The machine does good work but the manipulation of a pen that is only a holder and has no point is rather difficult.

Returned to the Library and worked from 4 to 630.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/18/2012 05:56 PM

76

Visited with Bogent and Oliver at the American Museum of Natural History all day 9 to 5, but spent some time in the Library. Met the director Parr, and others whom I had met before. Talked over the coefficient of divergence with (blank) who has gone more deeply into its variations and confidence limits than I am capable of. I hope that he will publish his results as they should serve to establish the coefficient of divergence as a useful statistic.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/18/2012 05:57 PM

122

Today went to Palm Springs with GG. Started at 10:30 AM. Cool and overcast.

1 Patchnose L DOR Top Poway Grade brush
1 Red Racer M DOR Lake Hodges Grass-Fields
Went via new 395, Hemet and Palms to Pines highway. Surprisingly few DOR snakes on the road. Few lizards.

Arrived at Palm Springs at 3:30 and put up at Tahquitz Vista. Warm but not hot. Saw Lloyd Mason Smith at the Palm Spring's Museum at 7 P.M. He gave me a number of snakes caught by himself and others left for me by Winfield H. Line.

Make a talk at the museum on rattlesnakes 8:05 to 9:20. A fair crowd. Saw Cowles for a few moments.

9:45 to 11 ran the road down to Cathedral City and then eastward on a new branch toward Date Gardens. This new road looks good. No travel and passes some sandhills. A cool quiet night no wind, no moon, but didn't see a thing alive or dead. Probably somewhat late.

Miles evening drive 26
Miles daylight drive 162.

Worked hard for 2.5 hours; almost got out but couldn't make it. Phil went over to a ranch house and got 5 Mexicans who got us out in a few minutes. Paid them $10. Saw Uta Stans here. Call it San Quintin.
Finally got back to Hamilton's Ranch (now run by Ray and Margarita Parodi) at 9:30 and had dinner.
Hyla regilla was heard and also what may have been Bufo californicus, but couldn't be sure of this.
Turned in at 11:30. Full moon.

158

Spent the entire day in experimental work, mostly on senses but decapitated 2 more. Tried all kinds of hearing reactions on a fine sensitive red diamond. Many times it seemed that hearing was involved, but always upon analysis it seemed that the snake sensed the vibrations of the container of some part of it, or my own movements.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

164

Spent most of the morning at the zoo because of various meetings.

In the afternoon, having made the decision after considerable thought and regret, I put aside section 7 on Habits and reverted to the descriptions of new subspecies -- Coronado oreganus, San Esteban molossus, El Muento mitchellis, andsouthern Willardi. Also the revival of helleri and cerberus. So I picked up the oreganus part where I had dropped it in March 1945; for the beginning of that paper and the attempt to gather data on habits for it were the forerunner of the expanded program that has engaged my attention during the subsequent 3 years, with 2 years or more still to go to finish it. But as the nomenclatural changes ought to be included in the Life History book, the quicker I make them the better, for this will reduce the changes in the final manuscript. Regretable but good judgment.

Made a good start picking up the oreganus problem.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/18/2012 06:20 PM
  • pamg 09/11/2012 02:23 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:54 PM

Had a can of rattlesnake for lunch this noon.

251

Left Tioga Lodge homeward bound at 7:50. Suddenly decided at Leevining to go over the Tioga Pass, and did so. Had some trouble with the car a/c thin atmosphere toward the top but made it ok. 1 striped racer S DOR about Oakhurst, Madera Co., exact location not recorded. Came out via Fresno, Bakersfield, & Pasadena. A little trouble getting gas o/c on strike. Very hot Fresno to Bakersfield. Reached home at 12:10 AM.

Miles today 528; a tough drive for an old man, especially with all the twisty mountain driving.

Total miles for the trip 1517.

318

Got some miscellaneous work done today on Chionactis but not too good progress.

Will see if I can drop it for awhile until all specimens are available and counted so that tabulations may safely begin.

Had a meeting of the Zoo board today from 12:30 to 3. I brought up the matter of the rattler book. Outlines its scope and the program. Told them it should be done in about 2-1/2 years. Would could about 10-12 thousand dollars for 1000 copies. Might sell at $5 or $6 each; so that eventually they might get back about half. Offered to put up $1000 to start a fund for its publication. They accepted; passed a resolution oking the deal. Appointed committee of Fred Annable, Fred Kunzel, and Dr. Berger to make recommendations re financing. Told them there was enough finished to make a worthwhile book if I should pass out leaving the rest unfinished. Thus I am relieved by the knowledge that a definite arrangement for publication has been consumated.

Page Edit History:
  • pamg 09/20/2012 03:49 PM
  • pamg 09/14/2012 10:08 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:54 PM
